Black history month 

Each February, all around the country, people come together to celebrate Black History Month. Since 1976, this month-long commemoration has honored the extraordinary achievements of African Americans. It has provided a special opportunity for all of us to reflect and recognize how far we’ve come and our powerful potential for the future.

This year can be an especially important Black History Month for our communities. We are still reeling from a tumultuous 2020. But through it, we have witnessed extraordinary displays of unity and resilience throughout the Black community. We remain determined to promote progressive change and equity in the face of systemic challenges and injustice. 

This spirit of perseverance and determination is echoed in the many stories of African American success. While this month might look different than in years past, it’s still important to find meaningful ways of creating joy, pride, and inspiration in our lives. There’s no better time than now — and no better way — than to spend time celebrating our remarkable and diverse culture.

At the core of this month is celebrating the strength, courage, and creativity of African Americans in the face of adversity. Start by exploring the untold stories of African Americans — from the music and films of our forebears to the groundbreaking innovations of the present day. Let the history of our struggle for equality drive us to call for justice and recognition today. 

The most meaningful way to recognize and celebrate Black History Month is to ensure our youth can benefit from a better tomorrow by making sure their education and opportunities are equitable. Encourage your children to do research and tell the stories of African American excellence. We can also help ensure their future by supporting African American businesses, charities, and causes.

Ultimately, the most impactful way to commemorate Black History Month is to commit to the ongoing struggle for access, justice, and equality in our own lives today. Thanks @grittyinpinklife for including me amongst these incredibly talented and beautiful women.

As a society, we still have a long way to go when it comes to recognizing and respecting the gender identity of transgender individuals. For many people, it can be difficult to understand or accept the idea that someone who was assigned male at birth can be a woman, or vice versa. However, gender is a complex and multifaceted part of our identity that goes far beyond the binary categories of male and female.

It’s important to remember that gender is not determined by what’s between our legs. Just as we wouldn’t ask someone we just met about their genitalia, it’s not okay to ask a transgender person about theirs. Additionally, everyone should have the right to make their own choices about their body, including gender-affirming care and abortion, especially when being guided by medical professionals.

In a video, @iamsheadiamond and @sander_jennings speak out against transphobia, and spread a message of equal rights for all. To all the transgender individuals out there: you are valid, you are loved, and you deserve to live your life on your own terms.
